The US War on Chinese Technology
NEW YORK – One of the worst foreign policy blunders made by previous generations (and even a few earlier ones) of Americans was the invasion of Iraq in 2003, under the pretext of eliminating – though such weapons did not actually exist – weapons of mass destruction.
The need to understand the erroneous logic behind that disastrous decision has become more pressing than ever before, because the same flawed reasoning is now being invoked to defend a similarly misleading US policy.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that we should act as if weapons of mass destruction were certain to fall into the hands of terrorists, even if the risk was small (for example, 1%).
This mode of reasoning almost always leads to bad decisions.
However, the United States and some of its allies are now using Cheneyism to attack Chinese technology.
According to the US government, since we cannot be certain that Chinese technology is safe, we should treat it as inherently harmful and ban it.
Correct decisions would apply probability estimates to various alternatives.
A generation ago, US policymakers should have considered both the purported 1% risk that weapons of mass destruction would fall into terrorist hands and the 99% risk of launching a war based on multiple flawed premises.
By focusing solely on that 1% risk, Cheney (as well as many others) diverted public attention away from the fact that the Iraq war lacked legitimacy and would significantly destabilize the Middle East and global politics.
But the problem with Cheneyism is not just that it acted on small risks without considering the high potential costs, but that politicians always stoke fear for some ulterior motive.
This is what American leaders are doing again: by pointing out and exaggerating some small risks, they are stirring up panic about Chinese tech companies.
The most relevant (but not the only) case is the US government's attack on the telecom company Huawei.
The US is gradually closing off its domestic market to the company and is trying to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the US may end up causing a senseless geopolitical disaster.
I worked in developing countries and have been following Huawei's technological progress because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide a tremendous impetus toward eradicating poverty and achieving other UN Sustainable Development Goals.
I have had similar interactions with other telecommunication companies and have encouraged the industry to enhance actions toward achieving these sustainable development goals.
I wrote a brief foreword (unpaid) for a report Huawei produced on this theme, which earned me criticism from those hostile to China. I asked industry leaders and government officials whether there was evidence of any misconduct by Huawei, and the recurring response was that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other credible industry leaders.
Despite this, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment could undermine global security.
U.S. officials claim that backdoors in Huawei's software or hardware could enable the Chinese government to conduct surveillance globally.
They point out that Chinese laws require Chinese enterprises to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are here.
Huawei's 5G equipment is affordable and of good quality, currently leading many competitors and has already begun deployment.
Its high performance stems from substantial investments in R&D over the years, economies of scale, and the company's experience navigating the Chinese digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology to their sustainable development, low-income economies around the world would be unwise to delay the rollout of 5G for much longer.
However, despite lacking any concrete evidence of backdoors, the U.S. continues to advocate for the world to avoid Huawei.
The U.S. argument is general.
As one U.S. Federal Communications Commissioner put it, "Countries that have 5G will lead in innovation and set the standard for the rest of the world, and that country is unlikely to be the U.S. at present."
Other countries — especially the UK — have yet to find any backdoors in Huawei's software or hardware.
Even if backdoors are discovered in the future, they are almost certainly fixable at that point.
About the debate over Huawei in Germany, where the U.S. government has threatened to cut intelligence cooperation unless authorities keep Huawei's 5G technology out.
Under pressure from the U.S., the head of German federal intelligence recently made a statement similar to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not an area where a completely untrusted group should be involved."
And he failed to produce any specific evidence of wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel has been working behind the scenes to open the market to Huawei.
Ironically, the U.S.' complaints partly reflect its own surveillance activities at home and abroad – although this is not news.
Chinese equipment might make it harder for the U.S. government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any government's unlawful surveillance activities should stop.
Independent oversight by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should opt for diplomacy and institutional safeguards rather than engage in a technology war.
The threatening impact of the U.S. demand to ban Huawei extends beyond the early rollout of 5G networks, posing significant risks to a rules-based trading system.
Now the United States is no longer the undisputed global leader in technology, and neither President Trump nor his advisors want to compete within a rules-based system.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
They are also attempting to cripple the dispute settlement mechanism of the World Trade Organization, further demonstrating their approach to global rules.
If the Trump administration can "successfully" divide the world into separate technology camps, the risk of conflict in the future will multiply.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade not only to increase global efficiency and expand the American technology market but also to reverse the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
And part of the reason for the collapse was the protectionist tariffs imposed by the US under the Smoot-Holley Act in 1930, which exacerbated the Great Depression, helped Hitler rise, and ultimately contributed to the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other areas, instilling fear and then acting on it — rather than following the evidence — is a path to destruction.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules, which is the safest course.
Let us establish independent oversight bodies to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to spy on others or launch cyberattacks.
This way, the world can quickly harness breakthrough digital technologies for global well-being.
